segments.text: We're presently in the office of Dr. Jack Hoblitzel in Ingleside, Texas.
The date is the 29th of October, 1982, and we're just going to discuss a little bit about his history and his past and so forth.
Let's start out, if you will, Dr. Hoblitzel, by giving your full name and your current address, and then we'll go on there with a little history of your life.
Current address here is Ingleside, Texas.
It's out in the country, Route 1, Box 1122.
It's on a Tyner Lane, 1225 Tyner Lane is the street address, and we're living about a mile out of downtown Ingleside, a small town of about 5,000 people, and we moved over here 19...
I sold a Windsor Park Animal Hospital to the two Dr. Pigott's in 56.
Moved over here and been here ever since.
All right, let's go back a little bit.
Let's go back to your birth.
When were you born?
I was born in Greene, Kansas, a little town outside of Clay Center.
Kansas.
Lived there till I was about four years old, four.
Moved to St. Joseph, Missouri.
Went to grade school in St. Joe for a year or two, and then we moved to the country about five miles south of St. Joe, Missouri.
Went to a little one-room schoolhouse where all eight grades were taught in one room called Stony Point School.
had as many as two or three eighth graders.
They'd teach every other grade, the seventh and eighth one, eighth one year, seventh and next, and sixth and fifth, fourth and the third, first and second.
When you attended, what grades did you use there?
I was there from the third grade on.
I think I went to McKinley High School
President McKinley.
McKinley High School, or grade school in St. Joe and then we moved to the country.
You have to say you got the basics there.
I got the basics out in the woods, out in Stony Point.
We used to have pie suppers.
Let me shut it off.
I went to Benton High School in St. Joe, Missouri from
out in the country, commuted back and forth, lived on the farm.
We had an 80 acres farm out there and graduated from high school in 1938.
I was in 4-H all my years from the 12th on.
I won two trips to Chicago in the 4-H.
Ordinarily, you only win one to get to go to the International at Chicago.
I won a trip in 1935, and my sister won one in 36, and then I won one in 37, I think it was, my second one, which was very unusual in that you only win one.
And I graduated from high school in Benton, high school in 38,
I immediately went to North Carolina, Gastonia, North Carolina to work for my uncle, Dr. Spring, and Dr. Ross had a hospital in Gastonia.
I worked there as a chemical boy.
Dr. Spring graduated from Veterinary Medicine at Kansas State.
Kansas State.
I think his graduation year was 32.
I'm not sure.
During the Depression.
Thirty-two?
Thirty, thirty-two.
He graduated a long time ago, all right.
He was in Gastonia.
Yeah, he was in Gastonia at the time with, in practice with Dr. Ross and while I was, I worked for him for a year and came back home and started into junior college.
making my pre-vet schooling in the junior college at home.
This is in St. Joe.
In St. Joe.
In the meantime, the war broke out.
I worked on the NYA and attended college and tried to make a living, worked for Sears, Roebuck's, making a few dollars to get through college.
In the meantime, Dr. Spring had
sold out in North Carolina and moved to Corpus Christi, Texas.
Never heard of the place before, and he just came here from North Carolina.
Yes.
The St. Joseph's of Missouri was a veterinary school, and you were acquainted with some of the old property there.
What did it look like to you at that time?
I was under Dr. Bailey.
He was the old instructor at the old St. Joe Veterinary College when it was still in operation.
The old school

was abandoned and he had about what year about what year in the late 20s I guess uh he he bought or leased rented I don't know how what he had the old veterinary school as his hospital for quite some time and I uh hung around with him quite a bit uh did he teach clinical medicine he taught he taught in the veterinary school and
He was one of the first men to diagnose anthrax on his own in those days, and they told him he was crazy.
Was he a bacteriologist?
He was a pretty good bacteriologist, I believe.
And he was a clinician?
Clinician for, in those days, he told me his story about his, when he diagnosed this anthrax and that he
injected his own guinea pigs and retrieved the organism from the guinea pigs and had his background pretty well when the state men told him he didn't know what he's talking about, I guess.
This was way back.
Did he have, well it must have been way back, about 1915 perhaps or so.
Yeah, it was in the early days.
Yes.
Did he have anything to do with the development of the vaccine, Carbazoo?
I don't think he did.
Of course, Ab Quinn, he knew Ab Quinn real good that started GenCell.
And Quinn was pretty well, he worked with Quinn and knew him pretty well.
They were buddies.
And I think Quinn was the one that developed the vaccine, more or less, back then.
What did you notice there in the veterinary school the buildings they had?

Well of course in those days it was a lot of horses and large animals and they had they had a stable in there the old school I don't know whether it's still standing or not it's right across from the police station in uh St. Joe there it was right south of the the police station uh I could
go there but I haven't been by to see if the building's still there.
How many buildings were there altogether?
It was just a big brick building.
One building?
With some classrooms and upstairs and then the main veterinary part was looked like a horse stable.
The clinic then was downstairs and the classrooms upstairs.
There was another old vet we used him on the farm by the name of Hokenbrink.
that lived, that practiced there before Dr. Bailey took it over.
Your intersection rooms were downstairs also for anatomy?
Anatomy and everything was.
In the meantime, some other officers and stuff had moved in, so I didn't know exactly what the veterinary school was like.
Yes.
But I do know there was, he practiced there in the old veterinary school.
But you finished then two years in junior college, is that right, or just one?
Two years, year and a half, two years.
Then you applied at Iowa State?
I applied to four different veterinary colleges, put in my application at Kansas State, Iowa State, Washington, and Colorado.
I had four different applications in and this was during the war.
We had declared war and
I hadn't gotten into any of the vet schools, and two days before college opened, I received a telegram to come to Iowa State.
I had never been there before, and I got in.
I think Bernie Waters was the man's place that I took his place in college.
Bernie joined the Navy.
and dropped out of his class and I took his place.
And then Bernie went to war.
He was from a small Iowa town, I think, and it got pretty hot on him on draft, so he just up and joined.
And this is my story as I understand it.
And then Bernie came back and finished vet school later.
But I took his position there.
in our class.
Your four years at Iowa State were rather uneventful.
We had three years at Iowa State, straight through.
Yes, but it was four years of veterinary school.
Four years of veterinary school in three years, straight through.
Seems we rather burned out that last summer, didn't we?
We burned out all the way through.
We kept grinding our, you know, we joined it.
We got to be in the service the last
15 months, which was the best thing that ever happened to me because I was about to run out of money.
I wondered where I was going.
You were too.
Yes, I know that.
You left there and immediately you came down and joined Dr. Spring in Corpus Christi.
In Corpus Christi.
We graduated from school.
They shipped us to Fort Sheridan.
Fort Sheridan gave us transportation back to our hometown.
And in the meantime, I had purchased a car from a barber there in Ames on Main Street, old Frank, old Buck, the barber.
I don't know whether you catch your hair or not, but old Buck sold me that 1940 Ford, and I drove it all the way to Texas.
I picked up Dr. Spring's wife out at Mount Hope, Kansas, and was down here three days later.
It started down with the...
It came to Corpus.
Never been in the state of Texas in my life, and started to work for Dr. Spring in 1944, right after we graduated, as soon as we got out of the Army.
He'd already been in practice here about five years, hadn't he?
Let's see, he moved, yeah, about three, four, let's see, 38, 39, or 40, about 40, about four years.
That was a 3500 Santa Fe, right?
Yeah, well, he bought... 4500 Santa Fe.
4100 Santa Fe.
He had bought the old vet, one of the oldest vet hospitals in Corpus.
He bought out there right by Spahn Hospital, right across the street, and then he moved out in the country and built that place.
It was way out in the country.
Then?
Then.
He built Spring Hospital, had lots of lawsuits, had to sue to get hooked up to water, and
They were going to stop him from building it.
He bought three acres out there in the country.
How could they sue him?
He wasn't in the city limits anywhere, was he?
Well, it was outside the city, but there was a water line going by there, and they wouldn't, he had to sue them to get hooked onto the water.
They were trying to keep him from hooking onto the water system.
There was a main water line going out of Santa Fe, out towards the cemetery there.
How did you find practice when you first began?
I've never known a slow day in my life, in my practice time, I don't believe.
We jumped in full feet, both always had more business than we, never looked for any business, always had more than we needed or wanted.
Could work seven days a week and long hours.
What did you feel were some of the greatest problems you encountered when you first began?
I know ticks were bad then.
Ticks were really bad.
I used to pick ticks before you had some insecticide that would, I think about the first one that came along that was really good was Carson's powder that helped us out a lot.
Mr. Carson down in the valley made that powder and shipped it all over the country.
It was a lifesaver for a long time.
Of course, Maine was real bad.
We still have DDT.
I think Maine's writing as of today is worse than I've seen it since I've been in practice.
Really, sarcoptic Maine.
I think it's probably due to
Not having DDT being banned, sarcoptic mange, is one of my big, big problems.
Okay.
As you got along, you stayed at Santa Fe yourself.
You bought out the practice then, didn't you?
I bought Doc Spring out.
I had Doc Spriggle came in with me, and he got called into the service.
They tried to call us back.
They called you back.
They tried to call me back and I had picked up undulant fever in the meantime working on some cattle and they didn't want me.
So I escaped the active service due to my undulant fever being pretty active at the time.
That was in about 1950 what?
When you bought out the hospital?
When I bought out the hospital?
I bought the hospital in
48, 49, I guess I'd have to go back and look at my papers, but I think it was around then.
I know Dr. Spriggle came in and worked for me.
Dr. Botard worked for me a little while.
See, he got on the state board.
Did you see that?
Botard is?
Botard is on the livestock commission.
Oh, he is?
They just appointed him.
Oh.
New appointment.
I saw it just the other day.

Botard worked for me for a little while, and Dr. Dwelley worked for us for a while, and Dr. Norton came down from Snow Blind and worked for a while, and let's see, there was quite a few people worked, you know, a short time, not as a more or less a training jumping off spot,
Then what year did you build the new hospital out at Windsor Park?
I built, I started it in 53, 52, 53.
I built, I worked on it.
I sold Dr. Sprigle, the old spring hospital, and built Windsor Park, ran it a couple years, and turn around sold it to Dr. Pike.
Moved over here in 50,

I bought this place in 55 and then I ran the hospital and ran back and forth from here and finally I decided just to I had Dr. Paget working for me his brother Richard and then Martin and Richard bought the place and I moved over here and that's where I've been ever since.
Your practice has been
Instead of here, although you've always claimed you've been semi-retired over here, what year did you move over here to Ingleside?
That is almost 30 years.
I was established, I built the hospital in 56, 57.
You've been here for 24 years.
Yeah.
I came over here, was going to slow down, got involved with a bad deal and had to keep going, working.
Well, the working hasn't hurt you any?
I've done large animal practice, quite a little bit of large animal, and then I've kind of gradually weaned it away and left it.
What are the biggest changes in practice that you've seen?
First of all, of course, your practice over there in Corpus Christi was mostly small animal.
What's been the big change in practice that you've seen from beginning to till now in small animal practice?
Well, in small animal practice, we worked with Dr. Green,
developing distemperoid vaccine, Dr. Spring did, and he was working with Dr. Green in developing the green method of vaccination.
I remember old virogen, three-shot method for distemper shots, and they were given those and not having too active an immunity.
Distemper is one thing that we don't see
a lot of like we used to.

I remember the distemper ward in North Carolina when we tried to immunize those foxhounds for those we had a lot of foxhound people over there that ran the whole packs of foxhounds and I remember those distemper hounds smell them and see them in my sleep and uh we came along when sulfa drugs were just coming out remember doctors sending me to the drugstore to get the

maybe a dozen pills of sulfathiazole and sulfadizine and sulfamethazine and all of these sulfas that came as they came out came out before we had penicillin nobody there wasn't a penicillin to be had we started getting a few bottles of penicillin bootleg so to speak from a naval base when they first the old aqueous penicillin
The vets that are graduating nowadays don't even know what it was like to practice without these antibiotics and all these sulfur drugs.
We didn't have them.
Of course, they didn't do much good for distemper.
No.
We thought they were going to do us a little good.
You know, we tried blood transfusion.
We tried making our own serum from dogs.
Anything to try to help.
and we didn't have too good a success.
We used many a dose of distemperoid direct from, from laboratories, shipped once a week, we'd get a supply into the hospital.
You used that in treatment at that time also?
We were treated, we used two double dose of them, we used it in every shape or form on Dr. Green's recommendation, trying to develop some type of protection.
I have a lot of fun kidding some of the young ones about they come in here and want to know about this new keroside medicine.
I pull out my old file and tell them, hell, I was treating dogs before you was born with that keroside.
And they said, oh, it's a new drug.
I said, no.
They said, you want to see my file?
And I grabbed this little file over here.
It's usually sitting right here on top.
I think I buried it here today.
You know, this kind of floor is a bunch of them.
I grabbed this file here, and I say, what new drug are you talking about?
We started keroside back in the late 40s.
Yeah, and I said, you want to see how long ago I treated dogs with keroside?
I said, here's a telegram.
You want to see it?
See that date on it?
I said, here's the old original.
I said, you want to see when we used it?
This is 18 January, 1949.
Here's a letter from Letterly Laboratories in February of 49.
Here's one in October of 48.
I said, that's how long I've been treating dogs.
We started treating dogs with kerosene way back in 48.
Now, this is not a new drug.
It's just a different form of it.
Yes, that's right.
And I said, that's the original pamphlet, right there.
Of course, the ethylcarbamidine was used, is now used to...
Prevent it.
Prevent it as a hilaricide.
At that time, we also had arsenical compounds that we began to treat the adult worms with, and of course, we had a lot of trouble with embolism until we learned to keep the dogs quiet.
Well, that was in the very early 50s and the late 40s.
Late 48, 49 when that was taking place.
They're still using kerosite and lots of it.
Cartworms still, still a scourge up here in Corpus Christi, aren't they?
Oh, man.
I don't think we have the, well, the ones that are really religious
and give it every day, and they do pretty good.
You're talking about the diethylcarbamazine.
Yeah, that's here.
Filler bits.
You can't hardly have a bird dog up here, unless you do it, however, because they just...
They won't last.
No.
See, that's distemper and heartworms.
Of course, you talked about sarcoptic manes off and on being bad.
The other infectious hepatitis never did get to be the big scourge they thought it would, did they?
No, and we had a dog show.
Lepto hit us one time real bad and wiped out a few.
Now I still think back sometimes I wonder whether we didn't have something similar to Parvo.
Remember that dog show that all those high-priced dogs died?
Were you here or do you remember that?
I don't recall that.
That was when?
Boy that was in 40, must have been around 48, 49.
There was a bench show in Corpus Christi?
They had a big dog show in Corpus and man champion boxers and champion this and champion that was just dropping dead and they overnight and I don't know whether a diagnosis was ever
We had what they called Virus X back in those days.
I don't know.
Do you remember Virus X?
No.
Huh?
No.
Virus X and the Coca-Cola being the treatment for it, vomiting.
I always had it turned over in my mind.
I wondered if Parvo wasn't there then.
Parvo wasn't back there and hit us like that because it killed them.
They just collapsed, just like this Parvo disease almost.
Bloody diarrhea.
Parvo started here in around 1979.
Just came in and wiped dogs out by the thousands.
What's it done now that three years has gone by in your practice?
Mine's slowed down.
I don't have too many of them.
I see one once in a while in a puppy, I think.
But as far as the major thing when it was wiping them out, it hit hard.
Oh, I'll tell you what was our biggest thing, and I'll
I don't know whether you had it, but it was the V.E.
epidemic of 1970.
Yes, it came through the valley first.
Go ahead tell us about what happened up here in Coastal Bend.
V.E.
hit here in July of 1970.
Seventy?
Was it?
Possibly or a little later.
July of 71.
This was probably our area was the hardest hit of any area.
I don't know whether the valley was hit as hard as we were.
The valley was hit very hard.
We lost probably before the vaccine was established we probably lost half the horses.
Half of your horse population?
July was red hot in here.
July 11th, 10th, 20th.
I'm just looking.
I lost 100 horses in my practice, which is a lot of horses.
And my daughter made this scrapbook out of all the articles.
It's surprising how, how it came in.
Here it is right there.
You see that?
Yes.
You said something you didn't like quarantine?
No, I wrapped the quarantine.
They, they act like it was going to stop at the New Asia River.
And they wouldn't give us any vaccine north of the New Asia River.
Oh really?
Yes.
The quarantine was lapped on and we couldn't get any vaccine.
And just because we lived on the other side of the river,
they wouldn't issue us any vaccine.
We lost, I talked to Dr., what's his name, out of King Ranch?
Morrill.
Morrill?
He came into my office here.
They didn't have any because they used the vaccine early, and we didn't get the vaccine until later.
That book right there has got the whole history of what happened here.
Surprisingly enough,
VWE came through, and of course we've all vaccinated since, but it's disappeared.
But do you realize they're still recovering the virus from mosquitoes in the valley?
Are they doing it here too?
Possibly.
They caught mosquitoes around here for a long time.
I haven't seen a mosquito man for a long time.
Well, that's very interesting that the virus is in the mosquitoes, but...
Hadn't hit the horses, huh?
A lot of vaccine and no more cases.
Well, I've vaccinated a pretty good percentage of the horses for three or four years afterwards.
Now, there may be a population of young horses and all that just kind of sneak back.
It could hit again sometime in the future.
Looking back on your practice, you know, we've had these viral enteritis symptoms.
of cattle.
Do you really think in your mind we had that back at the time that we graduated from school back in the early middle 40s?
What you mean BVD?
Yes.
About bovine virus diarrhea?
We probably did.
Didn't recognize what it was.
We call them bloody scars and passed them off as

I know I worked at feedlots when that BVD was so bad and we had one year it looked like we had pneumonia in cattle here that nothing phased nothing stopped and the medication you just well pour a bucket of water over top of them and do as much good as the medicine did.
And you were you've been pleased with the vaccines on uh on viral enteritis haven't you?
I think it's taken care of a lot of the problems.
I'm out of that type of practice right now.
I haven't been keeping up with it, but I did for a long time use the feedlots.
I had lots of lots of vaccine go through those feedlots and they they controlled it pretty well by vaccinating.
These suburbanites still love their horses, don't they?
Yeah, still going horse crazy.
My horse practice suffered considerable during the VE epidemic.
When you lose a hundred horses out of an area, it's noticeable.
And it didn't have a respect of the horses.
It didn't have to be a blooded horse.
It didn't have to be a nag.
When it hit, wiped them out.
You've been in veterinary medicine now for 40 years, counting some of the time you were in school, in the clinics.
As you look back on practice and so forth, do you have any comment on whether or not the profession could have done better, or that you could have done differently, or anything like that?
Or would you think things would have proceeded almost the same?
I think it probably proceeded just about the same.
I remember about 1940 when the investigator for the state association, no, let me see.
Yeah, he was with the state association.
It wasn't the board that he was with.
He was with the state association.
And we had an old plaque down there.
